Synchronous programming is a style of coding where the program executes one task at a time, in sequence. Each task must be completed before moving on to the next task. In JavaScript, this can be achieved through the use of callbacks or promises.
For example, consider a function that retrieves data from an API:
```javascript
function getData(url, callback) {
  var xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
  xhr.open('GET', url);
  xhr.onload = function() {
    if (xhr.status === 200) {
      var data = JSON.parse(xhr.responseText);
      callback(data);
    } else {
      console.log('Error!');
    }
  };
  xhr.send();
}
```
This function uses a callback to pass the retrieved data back to the calling function:
```javascript
getData('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/todos/1', function(data) {
  console.log(data); // logs [{ userId: 1, text: 'Hello ESL!', createdAt: '2018-05-06T07:00:00.000Z' }]
});
```
Asynchronous programming, on the other hand, allows multiple tasks to be executed at the same time. In JavaScript, this can be achieved through the use of callbacks, promises, or async/await syntax.
For example, consider a function that retrieves data from an API and performs some processing:
```javascript
function processData(url, callback) {
  getData(url, function(data) {
    var processedData = {};
    for (var key in data[0]) {
      if (key !== 'userId') {
        processedData[key] = data[1];
      }
    }
    callback(processedData);
  });
}
```
